00:02:05.044 --> 00:02:06.710
[INAUDIBLE] came up
with this great idea

00:02:06.710 --> 00:02:09.870
that I did last year--
is to take the life

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:13.260
cycle of the business and to
look at it through various sets

00:02:13.260 --> 00:02:14.900
of layers here.

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:17.990
Starting with intellectual
property, legal entity, people,

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:19.060
and financing.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:24.780
And across from pre- idea stage
all the way through financing.

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:27.470
So we're going to
walk through that.

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:31.910
And the first stage is going
to be the intellectual property

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:32.620
stage.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:33.960
And it's the idea part.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:40.240
And the question is who
owns the IP for the venture.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:43.894
And then the pre-
outside financing

00:02:43.894 --> 00:02:45.060
is, how do you protect that.

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:47.980
So that's the theme
for this part.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:51.390
Now how do we relate
to a business plan.

00:02:51.390 --> 00:02:54.440
And this is Fiona
Murray's Four Key Ideas

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.560
for Startups The first is
controlling the knowledge

00:02:58.560 --> 00:02:59.640
underlying an invention.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.560
If that's important to
your business success,

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:04.580
that's one of the
keys to startup.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:06.120
The second is secrecy.

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:11.460
Maybe nobody else knows
exactly how you do what you do.

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:12.540
The third is speed.

00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:14.950
Even with that other stuff
you need to move quickly.

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.740
And that could be a real
key advantage-- an idea.

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:19.177
And the fourth
thing-- in thinking

00:03:19.177 --> 00:03:21.010
about intellectual
property-- is there a way

00:03:21.010 --> 00:03:23.660
you could lock in customers.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:25.406
The way you go
about dealing with

00:03:25.406 --> 00:03:26.530
your intellectual property.

00:03:30.010 --> 00:03:33.650
And then how can that help
you in your business plan.

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:35.840
Well first of all, IP
is a valuable asset

00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:37.630
and you can use it
to raise capital.

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:40.000
One of the issues
with a lot of IP

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.610
is the investors don't
really understand what it is.

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:45.010
But they think it's important.

00:03:45.010 --> 00:03:47.280
And so if you don't
have some, they're

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:49.394
going to be questioning,
why aren't you

00:03:49.394 --> 00:03:50.310
doing something there.

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:53.660
So it's really a combination
of, is this important to you

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.280
and have you thought about it.

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:02.240
Now there is correlation
between IP and success.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:04.980
I did a study-- it was published
in the Intellectual Asset

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:10.580
Management publication-- in
which we run these analyzes

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:12.190
on venture backed companies.

00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:16.130
We run about 9,000 companies
through the set of metrics.

00:04:16.130 --> 00:04:20.079
And we took five top funds.

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:27.660
Kleiner Perkins, New
Enterprise, Domain-- and we

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:32.730
looked at patents
and we said, if we

00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:35.730
were to try to figure out
which companies had IP

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:39.660
and how good was their IP and
what was there success rates.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:41.170
We look at the
portfolios and said,

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:43.540
well we know some companies
have been acquired

00:04:43.540 --> 00:04:45.810
or they've gone public.

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:46.710
Those are winners.

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.020
And some companies
are out of business.

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:50.270
They failed.

00:04:50.270 --> 00:04:52.280
And then a bunch of
the other companies--

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:54.220
we don't know where
they are from a thing.

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:56.680
And what we did is we
looked at our rankings

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:58.370
based on analyzing IP.

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:03.410
And it turned out to 86%
of the winners scored high

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:05.410
in their patent strategy.

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:07.960
Which is sort of
interesting when you think.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:11.980
The Kleiner Perkins success
rate is one out of three.

00:05:11.980 --> 00:05:15.270
That is one out of
every three investments

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:17.980
that they make turns
out to be a success.

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:20.160
And they've got the best
track record out there.

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:24.910
So IP can really
correlate with success.

00:05:24.910 --> 00:05:26.430
The other thing
people look at is

00:05:26.430 --> 00:05:28.620
you can establish that
you are a good manager

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:31.070
of your technology.

00:05:31.070 --> 00:05:35.210
And that can help you in
on your business plan.

00:05:35.210 --> 00:05:37.600
Now I'm going to run two
different types of IP

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.970
protection, starting with none.

00:05:40.970 --> 00:05:43.850
And then trademark, copyright,
trade secret, patent,

00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:46.620
and combination.

00:05:46.620 --> 00:05:49.080
Now trademark and
copyright-- I'll

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:51.210
get into more detail--
but basically these

00:05:51.210 --> 00:05:53.370
are things that can
enhance your value.

00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:55.020
But they don't
necessarily block others

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:58.160
from doing what you're doing.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.300
Whereas trade secret
can prevent others.

00:06:01.300 --> 00:06:04.480
If they don't know how you
do it, they can't do it.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.900
And then patent is sort
of a combination of both.

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:09.950
Because in order to get
a patent, as you'll see,

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:11.949
you have to actually
disclose what you're doing.

00:06:11.949 --> 00:06:14.030
So you're telling
people the secret sauce

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:16.570
but you get some
rights in return.

00:06:16.570 --> 00:06:19.990
And then in some cases you get
combinations of protections.

00:06:19.990 --> 00:06:25.280
Like software can be protected
by copyright and by patent.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:27.820
So trademarks, what
are these things.

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:31.250
Well basically a
trademark is-- it can

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:34.150
be a name, a symbol, a sound.

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:36.360
Harley Davidson
actually trademarked

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:38.450
the sound of the vroom vroom.

00:06:38.450 --> 00:06:41.990
Color pink for insulation
is Owens Corning.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:44.930
And what it is--
it's something that

00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:51.290
tells a consumer that you're the
source of that good or service.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:55.600
So if I say Mercedes-Benz, you
have an image of what it is.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:07:00.730
So it connects the customer
with a particular source.

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:02.472
And it can be all
sorts of things.

00:07:02.472 --> 00:07:03.930
It can be a house
mark, which would

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:09.330
be IBM or Virtual Inc, which
is sort of the company names.

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:11.100
It can be a product mark.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:13.600
Like ThinkPad used to be IBM.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:16.040
Now a Lenovo product.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:20.130
And Mimio was the
virtual ink one.

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:24.900
The rights you get from
trademark arise through use.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:27.640
And if you register it you
get a whole bunch of benefits.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:30.280
And it's not very
expensive process to do it.

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:32.470
You should use a fanciful name.

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:35.780
So who would have thought
Apple for a computer.

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:38.700
That's a strong mark.

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:41.070
Don't pick something
that's merely descriptive,

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:48.080
like storage technology or
analog devices as a mark.

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:51.670
And for the business plan, if
you're putting it together,

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:54.230
you can actually check on
the availability of a mark

00:07:54.230 --> 00:07:59.970
by going to the USPTO and you
can search for a mark name.

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:02.530
Any questions on that so far?

00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:05.480
OK, so the next
one is copyright.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:08.440
So copyright is
basically the right

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:11.620
to prevent others from
making copies of what you do.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:13.700
And it rises just
from creating a work.

00:08:13.700 --> 00:08:15.370
So if I write a
letter to my mother,

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:18.910
I have a copyright in that.

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:21.610
Federal registration
is a plus in terms

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:24.780
of the ability to enforce that.

00:08:24.780 --> 00:08:28.090
It protects the expression,
not the function.

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:32.650
So I can actually copyright
my exact code in software.

00:08:32.650 --> 00:08:35.730
But I can't, through copyright,
prevent somebody else

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.164
from looking at the
code and writing

00:08:38.164 --> 00:08:40.580
equivalent kind of things, as
long as they are not exactly

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:41.260
copying it.

00:08:44.027 --> 00:08:45.610
Now for a business
plan, the key thing

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:50.040
with copyright that people
trip over is who owns it.

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:55.980
The owner of a copyright
is the author of the work,

00:08:55.980 --> 00:09:00.360
be it software, a
document, or whatever.

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:03.420
It's the author.

00:09:03.420 --> 00:09:07.700
Now unless that
author is an employee

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:11.750
and is generating that in
the course of employment.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:14.570
So if you go and hire an
independent contractor

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:17.800
to write code for
you, don't own it,

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:19.924
even though you paid for it.

00:09:19.924 --> 00:09:21.340
And so you've got
to make sure you

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:26.630
have an assignment of
ownership of that work to you.

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:28.410
Or when the investors
come in and they

00:09:28.410 --> 00:09:30.920
do their due diligence,
they're going to say,

00:09:30.920 --> 00:09:32.860
you don't actually own it.

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:35.060
I had a case back
in my law days where

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:37.490
someone paid over a half
million dollars for code

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:40.450
and couldn't actually
get ownership of it

00:09:40.450 --> 00:09:42.880
because he hadn't protected it.

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:46.671
And I also mentioned here, look
at open source as an issue.

00:09:46.671 --> 00:09:48.170
Where you're using
open source, make

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:52.050
sure you're complying with
the license for open source.

00:09:52.050 --> 00:09:55.280
Because investors, when they
come in-- you do all this work,

00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:57.416
you do your pitch.

00:09:57.416 --> 00:09:59.290
They send in the troops
to look you over then

00:09:59.290 --> 00:10:02.154
they find these landmines
you've planted there

00:10:02.154 --> 00:10:03.320
that you could have avoided.

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:06.830
So keep that in mind.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:09.390
Now trade secret
is what it says.

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:12.721
It's a secret it's something
that gives you, hopefully,

00:10:12.721 --> 00:10:14.970
an unfair competitive advantage
that nobody else knows

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:15.540
how to do.

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:19.480
And the most famous one is
the formula for Coca Cola.

00:10:19.480 --> 00:10:22.260
Which, I don't know whether
chemically you could figure it

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:24.240
out-- apparently nobody has.

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:25.630
But that's an example.

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:29.300
It's been a secret
for a long time.

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:30.020
I should back up.

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:32.480
A copyright is
effectively a long time.

00:10:32.480 --> 00:10:35.170
It's like 75 years.

00:10:35.170 --> 00:10:38.220
Trademark is indefinite as
long as you keep renewing it.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.900
Trade secret is indefinite
until it's finally

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:42.540
out there in the world.

00:10:42.540 --> 00:10:46.250
So you protect trade
secrets through

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:47.867
non-disclosure
agreements, if you're

00:10:47.867 --> 00:10:49.450
going to actually
have to describe it,

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:51.760
or you just don't
tell people about it.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:58.330
I think I'll just
leave it at that point

00:10:58.330 --> 00:11:02.020
The sort of big gorilla in
the IP spaces is patents.

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:05.090
Because they have much
stronger rights that you get.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:07.750
They're more expensive to get,
but they're stronger rights.

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:11.720
So a patent is really a
limited time monopoly.

00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:14.100
And we don't really like
monopolies in the US.

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:16.130
We have antitrust laws.

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:17.790
But in this case--
societal benefit,

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:19.414
it goes right back
to the Constitution.

00:11:19.414 --> 00:11:22.450
It says, look, we're going
to get ahead as a society

00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:25.680
if an inventor will
tell us how he did it.

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.150
And in exchange, we'll give
the inventor a limited time

00:11:29.150 --> 00:11:33.490
monopoly to prevent others
from doing something.

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:35.660
It has to be applied for.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:37.820
In the US, that's with
the patent office.

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:40.270
These patents are
country by country.

00:11:40.270 --> 00:11:44.420
In fact, most of these IP
rights are country by country.

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:45.540
Now, what do you get.

00:11:45.540 --> 00:11:49.140
Well, it's very much
like real estate.

00:11:49.140 --> 00:11:50.630
The fundamental
right-- and we'll

00:11:50.630 --> 00:11:52.730
go into a little more
detail in a moment--

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:55.650
is the right to prevent
people from trespassing

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:57.740
on your invention.

00:11:57.740 --> 00:11:59.790
So if you own a
piece of real estate,

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:02.270
your fundamental
right is, if I own

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:05.650
it and you walk on my
property, I can kick you off.

00:12:05.650 --> 00:12:08.000
Call the police,
get off my property.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.810
And that's essentially
what a patent does.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:12.810
The way it does that is
you could prevent others

00:12:12.810 --> 00:12:16.910
from making, using, selling,
importing, and distributing

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:18.160
your invention.

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:21.170
So you can't take something
that's patented in the US,

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:24.040
take it to a third, a
second, another country,

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:26.590
make it and bring
it back into the US.

00:12:26.590 --> 00:12:28.960
That would be an infringement.

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.990
Now the ownership of a patent
is not necessarily the right

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:34.310
to use it.

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:36.627
That's a hard one
to think about.

00:12:36.627 --> 00:12:37.460
What does that mean.

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:39.040
Well, think about real estate.

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:41.390
If my fundamental right
is, I can keep you

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:43.240
from walking on my
land, does that mean

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.360
I can actually use my land.

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:47.280
Well, maybe not.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:52.570
Suppose I have to walk across
your land to get to my land.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:55.010
I might not actually
be able to use my land

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:56.950
but I can certainly
keep you off of it.

00:12:56.950 --> 00:12:58.160
And so that's the analogy.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:00.790
Some people think that
it's a right to use.

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:03.830
It's really a right to exclude.

00:13:03.830 --> 00:13:06.320
And the claims in the
patent are like the fence

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:07.930
around the property.

00:13:07.930 --> 00:13:10.660
So those to find what
the legal property

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:13.600
is that you can
keep people out of.

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:15.680
And the duration is
20 years from the date

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:18.150
of filing under the new rules.

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:27.260
Now what do you have
to do to get a patent.

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:30.170
It has to be
something new, novel.

00:13:30.170 --> 00:13:33.610
And to get it, you have
to show the examiner.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:36.130
You make a filing
with the patent office

00:13:36.130 --> 00:13:38.420
and you have to
tell the examiner

00:13:38.420 --> 00:13:40.630
how yours is different from
what else is out there.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:42.060
Let's call prior art.

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:44.360
So you have to cite prior art.

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:46.370
So it has to be useful, also.

00:13:46.370 --> 00:13:49.680
That's not really an
issue for most patents.

00:13:49.680 --> 00:13:51.390
There's some pretty
un-useful things that

00:13:51.390 --> 00:13:54.250
have been patented out there.

00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:56.170
It has to be patentable
subject matter, which

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:59.150
is this whole thing we're
seeing now with business method

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:03.270
patents that I won't
go into any detail on.

00:14:03.270 --> 00:14:05.820
And it can't
previously have been

00:14:05.820 --> 00:14:09.020
sold or publicly described.

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:12.160
In the US you have
a one year window

00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:15.710
from the time you publicly
describe your invention

00:14:15.710 --> 00:14:21.070
or you put on the
market for sale.

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:24.390
You have one year in which you
get an application on file.

00:14:24.390 --> 00:14:28.640
And if you don't, you won't be
able to get a patent at all.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:32.900
Now the public description has
to be an enabling description.

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:35.100
So it has to be something
that actually explains it.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:36.670
So if I stood here
and said, I've

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:39.770
got this invention for
anti-gravity boots,

00:14:39.770 --> 00:14:42.730
I haven't told you anything
about how it's done.

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:44.290
So it has to be enabling.

00:14:44.290 --> 00:14:47.750
Now the other
requirement is that what

00:14:47.750 --> 00:14:50.500
you're trying to patent has
to be not obvious to one

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:53.720
of ordinary skill in the art.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:57.720
Now the word is ordinary
skill in the art.

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:00.360
I had a MIT professor
who decided, well,

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:03.860
this was sort of-- anybody
could have figured this out.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:06.940
Because he was used to dealing
at MIT professor level.

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:08.190
And so I said, I'm not sure.

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:09.898
You better go check
with a patent lawyer.

00:15:09.898 --> 00:15:11.890
And sure enough, it was
not something anyone

00:15:11.890 --> 00:15:14.550
with an ordinary skill would
have been able to figure out.

00:15:14.550 --> 00:15:20.000
Examples of overcoming that
part is that the prior art

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:21.640
teaches against it.

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:23.880
Other people say
it can't be done.

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:26.150
And you've shown it or
its commercial success.

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:27.850
Bob Langer does a
great story about some

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:31.000
of his early patents,
where he came in and showed

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:31.740
the examiner.

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:36.020
Look, if it was so obvious,
how come nobody else did it.

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:36.640
Nobody else.

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:38.820
And here are some papers
that said it can't be done.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:41.750
And that's how he overcame
his original set of issues.

00:15:45.002 --> 00:15:46.710
I hear a question?

