01:06:49.340 --> 01:06:49.840
funding.

01:06:53.900 --> 01:06:56.150
A typical way to do this
is you take a term sheet

01:06:56.150 --> 01:06:57.610
and you take it
apart and you talk

01:06:57.610 --> 01:07:01.180
about each of the little
components of the term sheet.

01:07:01.180 --> 01:07:03.610
And that's a useful
way to do it.

01:07:03.610 --> 01:07:05.460
I think the way
for an entrepreneur

01:07:05.460 --> 01:07:09.130
to think about why all these
terms is to understand what

01:07:09.130 --> 01:07:11.990
the major deal elements are.

01:07:11.990 --> 01:07:15.160
And from an investor viewpoint,
it's these four elements.

01:07:15.160 --> 01:07:19.050
One is a preferred return,
for reasons we'll talk about.

01:07:19.050 --> 01:07:22.920
Protection of valuation and
position versus future money

01:07:22.920 --> 01:07:24.590
that comes in.

01:07:24.590 --> 01:07:27.050
The requirement to manage
the investment and the exit

01:07:27.050 --> 01:07:29.540
strategy.

01:07:29.540 --> 01:07:32.990
So for example, if you
think a preferred return,

01:07:32.990 --> 01:07:38.770
an investor looks at you and
he sees a plan or a promise.

01:07:38.770 --> 01:07:40.120
The investor writes a check.

01:07:40.120 --> 01:07:42.690
The investor has
basically done everything

01:07:42.690 --> 01:07:44.820
that he said he would do.

01:07:44.820 --> 01:07:46.660
He'll be there to
advise and all that.

01:07:46.660 --> 01:07:48.250
But basically he'll
want his money.

01:07:48.250 --> 01:07:51.860
The entrepreneur
hasn't done anything

01:07:51.860 --> 01:07:53.110
from the investor perspective.

01:07:53.110 --> 01:07:56.900
They put together a plan
that's yet to be executed on.

01:07:56.900 --> 01:07:59.750
And so the result is
the investor typically

01:07:59.750 --> 01:08:04.010
wants to get paid before
the entrepreneur gets paid.

01:08:04.010 --> 01:08:05.750
He gets his money back first.

01:08:05.750 --> 01:08:08.150
And the instrument is usually
the convertible preferred

01:08:08.150 --> 01:08:10.260
stock.

01:08:10.260 --> 01:08:13.730
It usually has dividends.

01:08:13.730 --> 01:08:17.479
And an important part is
the liquidation preference.

01:08:17.479 --> 01:08:19.029
So the liquidation
preference says,

01:08:19.029 --> 01:08:21.020
look, there are two types.

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:23.750
One is a straight preference.

01:08:23.750 --> 01:08:26.850
It says, if the company-- we
have a liquidation-- which I'll

01:08:26.850 --> 01:08:30.060
talk about what that means
in a moment-- the investor

01:08:30.060 --> 01:08:33.560
can either choose
to get the money he

01:08:33.560 --> 01:08:36.000
put in back pluses dividends.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:38.920
Or you can convert, because
it's usually convertible,

01:08:38.920 --> 01:08:41.830
into whatever the convertible
amount of the company would be.

01:08:41.830 --> 01:08:45.010
So it's simply a math exercise.

01:08:45.010 --> 01:08:46.830
That's a straight
liquidation preference.

01:08:46.830 --> 01:08:49.520
A participating or
double dip is one

01:08:49.520 --> 01:08:53.340
that's not particularly good in
many cases for an entrepreneur.

01:08:53.340 --> 01:08:56.260
It says the investor
gets his money back first

01:08:56.260 --> 01:08:59.810
and then he converts and
pretends he was like you

01:08:59.810 --> 01:09:03.240
and gets a percentage
of the company.

01:09:03.240 --> 01:09:06.970
I put a chart in comparing
how that math works.

01:09:06.970 --> 01:09:08.930
I think it's pretty
self explanatory if you

01:09:08.930 --> 01:09:11.819
look at it in the materials.

01:09:11.819 --> 01:09:15.569
And I put a case in
here which says--

01:09:15.569 --> 01:09:16.870
there are two cases presented.

01:09:16.870 --> 01:09:20.060
One is, a founder sells 40%
of the company for $5 million

01:09:20.060 --> 01:09:23.760
of convertible preferred,
with a $5 million

01:09:23.760 --> 01:09:27.319
liquidation preference.

01:09:27.319 --> 01:09:28.899
But no participating rights.

01:09:28.899 --> 01:09:33.510
In Case B, they sell
33% of the company

01:09:33.510 --> 01:09:36.689
with participating preferred.

01:09:36.689 --> 01:09:40.130
And this example shows
you the trade off.

01:09:40.130 --> 01:09:43.050
Essentially, in this
case, if the exit

01:09:43.050 --> 01:09:46.330
is $35 million or less,
than the first case

01:09:46.330 --> 01:09:48.880
is better for the founders,
which means actually

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:51.250
giving up a bigger
percentage of the company

01:09:51.250 --> 01:09:53.337
and having a straight preferred.

01:09:53.337 --> 01:09:54.795
So take a look at
that after class.

01:09:58.360 --> 01:10:01.155
The liquidation events
could be really liquidation,

01:10:01.155 --> 01:10:03.300
meaning the company's shut down.

01:10:03.300 --> 01:10:06.810
But it's often defined
to be a merger.

01:10:06.810 --> 01:10:12.370
So if the company is acquired,
the liquidation kicks in.

01:10:12.370 --> 01:10:14.200
That's the preferred
return part as you

01:10:14.200 --> 01:10:17.480
look through the term sheet.

01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:19.420
The second major
element is protection

01:10:19.420 --> 01:10:22.470
of value and position
versus future money

01:10:22.470 --> 01:10:27.090
and that's where anti-dilution
protection comes in.

01:10:27.090 --> 01:10:30.690
And I give you an example
of a term sheet with that.

01:10:33.450 --> 01:10:37.430
Anti-dilution and
conversion go hand in hand.

01:10:37.430 --> 01:10:40.670
So typically, a
convertible-preferred

01:10:40.670 --> 01:10:41.920
trades one for one.

01:10:41.920 --> 01:10:44.800
One share of preferred
converts to one share

01:10:44.800 --> 01:10:46.860
of common at the beginning.

01:10:46.860 --> 01:10:48.930
And anti-dilution
says, if an event

01:10:48.930 --> 01:10:55.740
occurs in which you issue
stock for less money

01:10:55.740 --> 01:10:58.540
or priced less
than price I paid,

01:10:58.540 --> 01:11:01.790
then when I convert I
want to get more shares.

01:11:01.790 --> 01:11:05.300
Because your value of
the company's gone down.

01:11:05.300 --> 01:11:08.470
I came in at this level
and you did something.

01:11:08.470 --> 01:11:11.550
You didn't grow the company,
you made the value go down,

01:11:11.550 --> 01:11:13.500
and therefore I need
to get compensated.

01:11:16.310 --> 01:11:19.410
And the two main types of
these is the full ratchet,

01:11:19.410 --> 01:11:21.580
which is really bad
for an entrepreneur.

01:11:21.580 --> 01:11:24.550
That says if I issue
even one share of stock

01:11:24.550 --> 01:11:27.680
for less money than what
you, the investor, put in,

01:11:27.680 --> 01:11:29.820
then the price of that
one share of stock

01:11:29.820 --> 01:11:32.160
becomes a conversion price.

01:11:32.160 --> 01:11:37.640
So if I converted at $10 a share
and you issued one share at $1,

01:11:37.640 --> 01:11:40.880
now all my money
converts at $1 a share.

01:11:40.880 --> 01:11:43.046
So I get 10 times more.

01:11:43.046 --> 01:11:44.920
The more typical one is
the weighted average.

01:11:44.920 --> 01:11:46.420
And there's a formula
for that that.

01:11:46.420 --> 01:11:50.350
It looks at the
price and the amount.

